{
  "Question": "<p>If I have a function <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_191\"><math alttext=\"f(x)\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> defined as follows.</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_192\"><math alttext=\"f(x)=1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span> for all <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_193\"><math alttext=\"x&lt;1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span> and <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_194\"><math alttext=\"x&gt;2\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span>;</li> <li><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_195\"><math alttext=\"f(x)=100\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span> for <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_196\"><math alttext=\"x=1.5\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1.5</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span>;</li> <li><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_197\"><math alttext=\"f(x)\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> is undefined anywhere else.</li> </ul> <p>According to the <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_198\"><math alttext=\"\\varepsilon\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>\u03b5</mi></semantics></math></span>-<span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_199\"><math alttext=\"\\delta\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>\u03b4</mi></semantics></math></span> definition of continuity, if I take <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_200\"><math alttext=\"\\delta\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>\u03b4</mi></semantics></math></span> as any positive number smaller than <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_201\"><math alttext=\"0.5\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mn>0.5</mn></semantics></math></span>, then <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_202\"><math alttext=\"f(x)\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> by definition is continuous at <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_203\"><math alttext=\"x=1.5\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1.5</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span> because within the <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_204\"><math alttext=\"\\delta\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>\u03b4</mi></semantics></math></span>-neighborhood there is only one point defined, but <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_205\"><math alttext=\"f(x)\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> is obviously not continuous at <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_206\"><math alttext=\"x=1.5\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1.5</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span>.</p> <p>Below is the <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_207\"><math alttext=\"\\varepsilon\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>\u03b5</mi></semantics></math></span>-<span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_208\"><math alttext=\"\\delta\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>\u03b4</mi></semantics></math></span> definition of continuity:</p> <p>The function <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_209\"><math alttext=\"f(x)\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> is continuous at a point <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_210\"><math alttext=\"x_{0}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></semantics></math></span> of its domain if for every positive <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_211\"><math alttext=\"\\varepsilon\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>\u03b5</mi></semantics></math></span> we can find a positive number <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_212\"><math alttext=\"\\delta\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>\u03b4</mi></semantics></math></span> such that <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_213\"><math alttext=\"|f(x)-f(x_{0})|&lt;\\varepsilon\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">|</mo><mrow><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>-</mo><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">|</mo></mrow><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>\u03b5</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span> for all values <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_214\"><math alttext=\"x\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>x</mi></semantics></math></span> in the domain of <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_215\"><math alttext=\"f\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>f</mi></semantics></math></span> for which <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_216\"><math alttext=\"|x-x_{0}|&lt;\\delta\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">|</mo><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">|</mo></mrow><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>\u03b4</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span>.</p>",
